>
  <p>After a heart attack, recovery depends on the extent of damage to the heart, particularly the left ventricle's ability to pump blood effectively.</p>

  <p>Emergency coronary angiography improves immediate survival but does not treat the underlying disease, requiring long-term treatment. Medications include aspirin for blood thinning, antihypertensives and blood sugar treatments if necessary.</p>

  <p>Lifestyle changes are essential: a suitable diet, regular physical activity, smoking cessation and optimal management of hypertension, diabetes and cholesterol.</p>

  <p>Regular cardiology consultations allow follow-up and treatment adjustment. This follow-up combined with lifestyle changes reduces the risk of complications and improves quality of life.</p>
